Fuzzy Landscapes - A reproducible approach to analyse uncertain parameters

Wolfgang Hamer & Daniel Knitter

19 September 2018

Exemplary Aim

  • Identify potential vegetation cover around ukrainian mega-site of Maidanetske (3850-3700 BCE) under different climatic conditions

Potential vegetation

  • Identification of potential vegetation by application of adapted Ellenberg Diagram

Problem

  • How to deal with the assumption of different climatic conditions?
  • How to calculate with terms like dry or wet?

FuzzyLandscapes

The FuzzyLandscapes package enables the user to:

  • Express fuzzy terms spatially by applying mathematical functions to crisp raster datasets
  • Combine those fuzzy raster datasets by rule-based systems

1. Download of elevation information for specific region

library(raster)

Maidanetske <- readOGR(dsn = "./data/Megasites", layer = "Tripolye_mega-sites_polygons", verbose=FALSE) %>% 
  spTransform(., CRS("+init=epsg:4326")) %>% 
  '['(which(.@data$site=="Maidanetske"),)

srtm <- getData('SRTM', 
                lon=mean(extent(Maidanetske)[c(1,2)]), 
                lat=mean(extent(Maidanetske)[c(3,4)]))
plot(crop(srtm,extent(Maidanetske)+0.2))
lines(Maidanetske,col="red")

2. Derive information of elevation model

Using the package RQGIS to apply saga:sagawetnessindex to derive the potential wetness of the area

3. Download of soil data

  • Download of sand, silt and clay content from the GlobalSoilGrid WCS Server

4. Fuzzification of the crisp data

library(FuzzyLandscapes)
dry <- fl_create_ras(method = "trapezoid",rast = swi,
                     p1=2,p2=3,p3=7,p4=8.5, setname = "dry")

moderately_dry <- fl_create_ras(method = "trapezoid",rast = swi,
                                         p1=7,p2=8.5,p3=8.5,p4=9.5, setname = "moderately_dry")

fresh_to_moist <- fl_create_ras(method = "trapezoid",rast = swi,
                                         p1=8.5,p2=9.5,p3=10,p4=10.5, setname = "fresh_to_moist")

moist_to_wet <- fl_create_ras(method = "trapezoid",rast = swi,
                                         p1=10,p2=10.5,p3=11.5,p4=12, setname = "moist_to_wet")

wet <- fl_create_ras(method = "trapezoid",rast = swi,
                                         p1=11,p2=12,p3=15,p4=16, setname = "wet")

plot_fs_comb(dry,moderately_dry,fresh_to_moist,moist_to_wet,wet,
             cols = colorRampPalette(c("gold","blue")))

Fuzzified raster data

5. Definition of rules to combine the datasets

Val1 Op1 Val2 Op2 Val3 Op4 Result
sand_high and clay_low and silt_low then fine_sand
sand_high and clay_low and silt_medium then loamy_sand
sand_medium and clay_low and silt_medium then sandy_loam
sand_medium and clay_medium and silt_medium then loam
clay_medium or clay_high then medohigh_clay
sand_low and medohigh_clay and silt_medium then loam_partly_clay
dry then Grassland
moderately_dry or fresh_to_moist then dry_or_mod
dry_or_mod and fine_sand then Pineto_quercetum
dry_or_mod and loamy_sand then Open_woodland
moderately_dry and sandy_loam then Open_woodland
moderately_dry and loam then Open_woodland
loam or loam_partly_clay then loa_or_pac
moderately_dry and loa_or_pac then Grassland
loa_or_pac or sandy_loam then loa_pac_or_sa
fresh_to_moist and loa_pac_or_sa then Closed_canopy
fresh_to_moist and loam_partly_clay then Grassland
moist_to_wet and fine_sand then Pinus
moist_to_wet and loamy_sand then Open_woodland
moist_to_wet and loa_pac_or_sa then Closed_canopy
wet and fine_sand then Pinus
wet and loa_pac_or_sa then Alder_carr

6. Application of defined rules on the fuzzified datasets

whattodefuzz <- c("Grassland","Pineto_quercetum","Open_woodland","Closed_canopy","Pinus","Alder_carr")
fuzzystack <- fl_frbs_stack(sand_low,sand_medium,sand_high,
                            silt_low,silt_medium,silt_high,
                            clay_low,clay_medium,clay_high,
                            dry,moderately_dry,fresh_to_moist,moist_to_wet,wet,
                            rules = as.data.frame(ruleda),
                            result_intersect = TRUE,
                            defuzzification = whattodefuzz)
plot(crop(fuzzystack$FuzzyResults[[whattodefuzz]],extent(Maidanetske)+0.2),nc=6,breaks=seq(0,1,.1),col=colorRampPalette(c("honeydew","green","green3"))(11))

Defuzzified classes

Scenario Dry

changeby <- 2
dry <- fl_create_ras(method = "trapezoid",rast = swi,
                     p1=2,p2=3,p3=7+changeby,p4=8.5+changeby, setname = "dry")
moderately_dry <- fl_create_ras(method = "trapezoid",rast = swi,
                                p1=7+changeby,p2=8.5+changeby,p3=8.5+changeby,p4=9.5+changeby, setname = "moderately_dry")
fresh_to_moist <- fl_create_ras(method = "trapezoid",rast = swi,
                                p1=8.5+changeby,p2=9.5+changeby,p3=10+changeby,p4=10.5+changeby, setname = "fresh_to_moist")
moist_to_wet <- fl_create_ras(method = "trapezoid",rast = swi,
                              p1=10+changeby,p2=10.5+changeby,p3=11.5+changeby,p4=12+changeby, setname = "moist_to_wet")
wet <- fl_create_ras(method = "trapezoid",rast = swi,
                     p1=11+changeby,p2=12+changeby,p3=15+changeby,p4=16+changeby, setname = "wet")

plot_fs_comb(dry,moderately_dry,fresh_to_moist,moist_to_wet,wet,
             cols = colorRampPalette(c("gold","blue")))

Outlook

Next steps:

  • Implementation of distance to settlement?

Conclusion

FuzzyLandscapes allows working with fuzzy terms like high, low, close, far, steep or flat by

  • Fuzzification of crisp raster data
  • Rule-based combination of fuzzy datasets
  • Defuzzification of those combined datasets

Try it out in your specific field and let us know about your experience with FuzzyLandscapes (https://gitlab.com/CRC1266-A2/FuzzyLandscapes)
